  <subsection xml:id="subsec-properties-of-vectors">
    <title>Properties of Addition, Length, and Scalar Multiplication</title>
    <definition xml:id="def-properties-of-vectors">
      <title>Properties of Vectors</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, and <m>\mathbf{w}</m> are vectors, <m>\mathbf{0}</m> is the zero vector, and <m>c</m> and <m>d</m> are scalars, then
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Vector Addition</em>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{u}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\mathbf{u}+(\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{w})=(\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v})+\mathbf{w}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{0}=\mathbf{u}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\mathbf{u}+(-\mathbf{u})=\mathbf{0}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Length of a Vector</em>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\|c\mathbf{u}\|=|c|\|\mathbf{u}\|</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Scalar Multiplication</em>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>c(\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v})=c\mathbf{u}+c\mathbf{v}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(c+d)\mathbf{u}=c\mathbf{u}+d\mathbf{u}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(cd)\mathbf{u}=c(d\mathbf{u})=d(c\mathbf{u})</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>1\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{u}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>0\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{0}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>c\mathbf{0}=\mathbf{0}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove 1, 5, 6 and leave the rest as exercises
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          solution
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-finding-unit-vector">
    <title>Finding a Unit Vector</title>
    <p>
      Sometimes it is useful to look at problems involving vectors in terms of a vector in the same direction, but with a magnitude of one. Recall that a unit vector <m>\mathbf{u}</m> is a vector whose length is one, <m>\|\mathbf{u}\|=1</m>. To find a unit vector in the same direction, you will need to divide that vector by its length or magnitude.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-unit-vector-same-direction">
      <title>Unit Vector That Has the Same Direction as <m>\mathbf{v}</m></title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\mathbf{v}</m> be any vector. The vector
          <me>
            \mathbf{u}=\frac{\mathbf{v}}{\|\mathbf{v}\|}
          </me>
          is a <term>unit vector</term><idx><h>unit vector</h><h>same direction as <m>\mathbf{v}</m></h></idx> that has the same direction as <m>\mathbf{v}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the unit vector that has the same direction as <m>\mathbf{v}=\langle10,-5\rangle</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          From <xref ref="ex_magnitude">Example</xref>, we know <m>\|\mathbf{v}\|=5\sqrt{5}</m>. Then
          <me>
            \mathbf{u}=\frac{\mathbf{v}}{\|\mathbf{v}\|}=\frac{\langle10,-5\rangle}{5\sqrt{5}}=\left\langle\frac{10}{5\sqrt{5}},-\frac{5}{5\sqrt{5}}\right\rangle=\left\langle\frac{2}{\sqrt{5}},-\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}\right\rangle=\left\langle\frac{2\sqrt{5}}{5},-\frac{\sqrt{5}}{5}\right\rangle
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          We can verify that this is in fact a unit vector by computing the magnitude:
          <me>
            \|\mathbf{u}\|=\left\|\left\langle\frac{2\sqrt{5}}{5},-\frac{\sqrt{5}}{5}\right\rangle\right\|=\sqrt{\left(\frac{2\sqrt{5}}{5}\right)^2+\left(-\frac{\sqrt{5}}{5}\right)^2}=\sqrt{\frac{4\cdot5}{25}+\frac{5}{25}}=\sqrt{\frac{25}{25}}=1
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      Two useful unit vectors are <m>\mathbf{i}</m> and <m>\mathbf{j}</m>. The vector <m>\mathbf{i}</m> represents the unit vector whose direction is along the positive <m>x</m>-axis and the vector <m>\mathbf{j}</m> represents the unit vector whose direction is along the positive <m>y</m>-axis.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-i-j-vectors">
      <title><m>\mathbf{i}</m> and <m>\mathbf{j}</m></title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The unit vectors <m>\mathbf{i}</m> and <m>\mathbf{j}</m> are defined as
          <me>
            \mathbf{i}=\langle1; \quad0\rangle,\mathbf{j}=\langle0,1\rangle
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      We can now represent any vector using the unit vectors <m>\mathbf{i}</m> and <m>\mathbf{j}</m>.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-vector-horizontal-vertical-components">
      <title>Horizontal and Vertical Components of a Vector</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\mathbf{v}</m> be any vector. Then we can express <m>\mathbf{v}</m> in terms of its <term>horizontal</term> and <term>vertical components</term><idx><h>vectors</h><h>components of</h></idx>
          <me>
            \mathbf{v}=\langle v_x,v_y\rangle=v_x\mathbf{i}+v_y\mathbf{j}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-vector-components-and-direction">
    <title>Vector Components and Direction</title>
    <p>
      Recall that a vector is composed of a direction and magnitude. Earlier in this section we learned how to calculate the magnitude. Now we will discuss how to calculate the direction.
    </p>
    <definition xml:base="def-direction">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\mathbf{v}=\langle v_x,v_y\rangle</m> be a vector with magnitude <m>\|\mathbf{v}\|</m>.
          The angle <m>\theta</m> represents the <term>direction</term>
              <idx><h>vectors</h><h>direction</h></idx>
          of <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and is the smallest positive angle in standard position formed by the positive <m>x</m>-axis and <m>\mathbf{v}</m>
          (<m>0^{\circ}\leq\theta\leq360^{\circ}</m>).
          The direction, <m>\theta</m> and can be calculated by
          <me>
            \theta=\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{v_y}{v_x}\right)
          </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      We now have all the information needed to write a vector.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-horizontal-vertical-components-from-magnitude-direction">
      <title>Finding Horizontal and Vertical Components of Vectors from Magnitude and Direction</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m> with magnitude <m>\|\mathbf{v}\|</m> and direction <m>\theta</m>, we can use Right Triangle Trigonometry to solve for the horizontal and vertical components, denoted as <m>v_x</m> and <m>v_y</m>, respectively:
          <me>
            v_x=\|\mathbf{v}\|\cos\theta, \quad v_y=\|\mathbf{v}\|\sin\theta
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          This allows us to express <m>\mathbf{v}</m> as
          <me>
            \mathbf{v}=\|\mathbf{v}\|\cos\theta\mathbf{i}+\|\mathbf{v}\|\sin\theta\mathbf{j}=\langle\|\mathbf{v}\|\cos\theta,\|\mathbf{v}\|\sin\theta\rangle
          </me>
        </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-vector-components-angle">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.75]
            \draw[stealth-stealth] (-1,0)--(13,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
            \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,-1)--(0,7) node[above]{\(y\)};
            \draw[line width=2pt,blue,-stealth](0,0) -- (10,6) node[black,midway,below]{\(\mathbf{v}\)};
            \draw (0,0) -- (0:1.2cm) arc (0:atan2(6,10):1.2cm) node at (15:1.6cm) {\(\theta\)} -- cycle;
            \draw[dashed] (10,6)--(10,0);
            \draw [decorate,decoration={brace,amplitude=10pt,mirror},xshift=0.4pt,yshift=-0.4pt](0,0) -- (10,0) node[black,midway,yshift=-0.6cm] { \(a=\|\mathbf{v}\|\cos\theta\)};
            \draw [decorate,decoration={brace,amplitude=10pt,mirror},xshift=0.4pt,yshift=0.4pt](10,0) -- (10,6) node[black,midway,xshift=1.35cm] { \(b=\|\mathbf{v}\|\sin\theta\)};
            \draw [decorate,decoration={brace,amplitude=10pt,mirror},xshift=0.4pt,yshift=-0.4pt](10,6) -- (0,0) node[black,midway,yshift=0.6cm,xshift=-0.4cm] { \(\|\mathbf{v}\|\)};
            \draw (9.1,0) -- (9.1,0.9) -- (10,0.9);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-velocity">
    <title>Velocity</title>
    <p>
      Vectors can represent various physical objects. For instance, the velocity of a moving waʻa (canoe) is depicted by a vector. This velocity vector indicates the direction of motion and the speed of the waʻa. It is called the <term>velocity vector</term><idx><h>vectors</h><h>velocity</h></idx> and can also describe other physical phenomena such as wind and currents.
    </p>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Wind is blowing from the house Nā Leo Hoʻolua (N<m>22.5^{\circ}</m>W) at 10 knots. Write the wind velocity as a vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First, we note that since the velocity is 10 knots, we have <m>\|\mathbf{v}\|=10</m>. Next, we need to find the direction. Since <m>\theta</m> is measured from the positive <m>x</m>-axis, by <xref ref="def-horizontal-vertical-components-from-magnitude-direction"/> we see that
          <me>
            \theta=90^{\circ}+22.5^{\circ}=112.5^{\circ}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          To find the vector, will need the horizontal and vertical components:
          <md>
            <mrow>v_x =\amp \|\mathbf{v}\|\cos\theta=10\cos112.5^{\circ}\approx-3.8</mrow>
            <mrow>v_y =\amp \|\mathbf{v}\|\sin\theta=10\sin112.5^{\circ}\approx9.2</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Thus
          <me>
            \mathbf{v}\approx-3.8\mathbf{i}+9.2\mathbf{j}=\langle-3.8,9.2\rangle
          </me>
        </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-exampl-vector-velocity" width="50%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
            \draw[stealth-stealth] (-5,0)--(3,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
            \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,-1)--(0,10) node[above]{\(y\)};
            \draw[-stealth, line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (112.5:10) node[midway,below,xshift=-3]{\(\mathbf{v}\)};
            \draw[-stealth, line width=1.25pt] (0:2) arc (0:112.5:2) node[midway, right,xshift=0.1cm,yshift=2] {\(\theta=112.5^{\circ}\)};
            \draw[-stealth, line width=1.25pt] (90:3) arc (90:112.5:3) node[midway, above,yshift=0.2cm,xshift=-0.05cm] {\(22.5^{\circ}\)};
            \draw[-stealth, line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (-3.82683432365,0) node[midway,below,xshift=-3,yshift=-2]{\(3.8\)};
            \draw[-stealth, line width=2pt,blue] (-3.82683432365,0) -- (-3.82683432365,9.23879532511) node[midway,left,xshift=-3]{\(9.2\)};
            \draw (-3.02683432365,0) -- (-3.02683432365,0.8) -- (-3.82683432365,0.8);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="example-speed-with-current-drift">
      <title>Calculating Canoe Velocity with Current Drift</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          The vaka Marumaru Atua<idx><h>canoe</h><h>Marumaru Atua</h></idx> sets sail on a voyage northward from Rarotonga to Hawaiʻi, maintaining a steady speed of 5 knots through the water. However, a 1-knot current flows in the direction of Lā Kona (a heading of 260 degrees). This current's influence resembles walking on a moving treadmill, where forward progress is limited despite moving legs. Similarly, Marumaru Atua navigates while the water, in the form of a current, also moves. The actual velocity of Marumaru Atua is the resultant of the canoe's velocity and the current's velocity. This resultant velocity vector, known as the velocity over ground (VOG), denotes the canoe's speed and direction relative to fixed objects on Earth, influenced by the current's impact on Marumaru. The magnitude of this velocity vector, called the <term>speed over ground (SOG)</term>,<idx><h>speed over ground</h></idx> represents the absolute speed of the canoe relative to fixed objects, accounting for both the canoe's speed through the water and the current's speed and direction.
        </p>
