      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Express Marumaru Atua's velocity vector, represented as <m>\mathbf{v}_m</m>, and the velocity vector of the current, denoted as <m>\mathbf{v}_w</m>, in terms of their horizontal and vertical components. Round your answer to two decimal places.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            First, we draw the velocity vectors for Marumaru Atua and the current:
          </p>
          <image xml:id="fig-marumaru-current-vectors" width="60%">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
              \draw[thin,gray!40] (-4,-2) grid (4,6);
              \draw[-stealth] (0,0) -- (0,6) node[above] {N};
              \draw[-stealth] (0,0) -- (0,-2) node[below] {S};
              \draw[-stealth] (0,0) -- (4,0) node[right] {E};
              \draw[-stealth] (0,0) -- (-4,0) node[left] {W};
              \draw[line width=2pt,black,-stealth](0,0) -- (0,5) node[midway,right] {\(\mathbf{v}_m\)};
              \draw[line width=2pt,blue,-stealth](0,0) -- (190:1) node[midway,below] {\(\mathbf{v}_c\)};
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          <p>
            Since Marumaru Atua is sailing north at 5 knots, the velocity is:
            <me>
              \mathbf{v}_m=\langle0,5\rangle.
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            To find the vector for the current, we need to know <m>t</m>, the angle of the velocity vector in standard position (see <xref ref="def-standard-position"/>). We begin by drawing the heading angle of <m>260^{\circ}</m> and its reference angle, <m>t'</m>.
          </p>
          <image xml:id="fig-marumaru-heading-reference-angle" width="60%">
            <shortdescription>Illustration of the heading angle and its reference angle</shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
              \draw[stealth-stealth] (-3.25,0)--(3.25,0) node[right]{$x$};
              \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,-3.25)--(0,3.25) node[above]{$y$};
              \filldraw[blue] (3,0) circle(1pt);
              \filldraw[blue] (190:3.2) circle(1pt);
              \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (3,0);
              \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (190:3.2);
              \draw[-stealth, line width=1.25pt] (90:2.7) arc (90:-170:2.7) node[midway,
              right,xshift=0.05,yshift=-0.2] {\(260^{\circ}\)};
              \draw[-stealth, line width=1.25pt] (180:2.2) arc (180:190:2.2) node[midway,
              right,xshift=0.05,yshift=-0.2] {\(t'\)};
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          <p>
            We can see from the figure that <m>260^{\circ}+t'=270^{\circ}</m>, thus we get our reference angle as
            <me>
              t'=10^{\circ}
            </me>.
          </p>
          <p>
            We now draw our angle, <m>t</m>, in standard position and the reference angle, <m>t'</m>:
          </p>
          <image xml:id="fig-marumaru-standard-angle" width="60%">
            <shortdescription>Illustration of the angle t in standard position and the reference angle t'</shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
              \draw[stealth-stealth] (-3.25,0)--(3.25,0) node[right]{$x$};
              \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,-3.25)--(0,3.25) node[above]{$y$};
              \filldraw[blue] (3,0) circle(1pt);
              \filldraw[blue] (190:3.2) circle(1pt);
              \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (3,0);
              \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (190:3.2);
              \draw[-stealth, line width=1.25pt] (0:2.7) arc (0:190:2.7) node[midway,
              above] {\(t\)};
              \draw[-stealth, line width=1.25pt] (180:2.2) arc (180:190:2.2) node[
              below] {\(10^{\circ}\)};
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          <p>
            From <xref ref="rem-calculate-angle-given-quad-reference-angle"/>, we have
            <me>
              t=180^{\circ}+10^{\circ}=190^{\circ}
            </me>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Thus, by <xref ref="def-horizontal-vertical-components-from-magnitude-direction"/> the velocity for the current is
            <me>
              \mathbf{v}_c=\langle1\cdot\cos190^{\circ},1\cdot\sin190^{\circ}\rangle\approx\langle-0.98,-0.17\rangle.
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find <m>\mathbf{v}_g</m>, the velocity of Marumaru Atua relative to fixed objects on the ground.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The velocity relative to fixed objects on the ground is the sum of the two vectors:
            <md>
              <mrow> \mathbf{v}_g=\mathbf{v}_m+\mathbf{v}_c \amp = \langle0,5\rangle+\langle-0.98,-0.17\rangle </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = \langle-0.98,5-0.17\rangle </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = \langle-0.98,4.83\rangle </mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            This can visually demonstrated in the figure below
          </p>
          <image xml:id="fig-marumaru-sog" width="60%">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
              \draw[thin,gray!40] (-4,-2) grid (4,6);
              \draw[-stealth] (0,0) -- (0,6) node[above] {N};
              \draw[-stealth] (0,0) -- (0,-2) node[below] {S};
              \draw[-stealth] (0,0) -- (4,0) node[right] {E};
              \draw[-stealth] (0,0) -- (-4,0) node[left] {W};
              \draw[line width=2pt,black,-stealth](0,0) -- (0,5) node[midway,right] {\(\mathbf{v}_m\)};
              \draw[line width=2pt,blue,-stealth]([shift=(90:5)]0,0) -- ([shift=(90:5)]190:1) node[midway,above] {\(\mathbf{v}_c\)};
              \draw[line width=2pt,black,-stealth](0,0) -- ([shift=(90:5)]190:1) node[midway,left] {\(\mathbf{v}_g\)};
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the speed over ground (SOG) and direction of Marumaru Atua, rounded to one decimal place.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The actual speed of Marumaru Atua is simply the magnitude of the velocity over ground:
            <me>
              \|\mathbf{v}_g\|=\|\langle-0.98,4.83\rangle\|=\sqrt{(-0.98)^2+(4.83^2)}\approx4.9\mbox{ knots}.
            </me>
            Thus, although the vaka sails through the water at 5 knots, its forward progress is slightly slower at 4.9 knots.
          </p>
          <p>
            To find the direction of the velocity, we use <xref ref="def-direction"/> to get
            <me>
              \theta=\tan^{-1}\frac{v_y}{v_x}=\tan^{-1}\frac{4.83}{-0.98}\approx-78.5^{\circ}
            </me>.
            Since our velocity vector is in Quadrant II, we have our direction is
            <me>
              180^{\circ}-78.5^{\circ}=101.5^{\circ}
            </me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="examp-leeway">
      <title>Leeway</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          When a waʻa sails on the ocean, it rarely moves precisely in the direction it's pointed. One reason for this is that crosswind can push the waʻa off its course. The angle of displacement between the apparent heading of the waʻa and the direction the waʻa is actually traveling through the water is referred to as <em>leeway</em>.<idx><h>leeway</h></idx> Using vector addition, we can determine where the waʻa will actually travel. However, on the waʻa, the navigator can determine the leeway by observing the angle from the wake behind the waʻa and the apparent direction the waʻa is pointed towards.
        </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-leeway">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[thin,gray!40] (-7,-7) grid (7,7);
            \draw[line width=1pt,-stealth,dashed](-6,5) -- (6,-5) node[black,right,xshift=-30,yshift=50,text width=1.3cm]{ Apparent Heading of Wa`a};
            \draw[line width=1pt,blue,-stealth,decorate,decoration=snake](0,0) -- (-3,6) node[black,right]{ Wake of Wa`a};
            \draw[line width=1pt,blue,dashed,-stealth](0,0) -- (3,-6) node[black,left,xshift=-15,yshift=20,text width=1.3cm]{ Actual Heading of Wa`a};
            \draw[-stealth,line width=2pt](3,1) -- (0,0) node[black,sloped,midway,above]{ Wind};
            \draw[-stealth,line width=2pt](6,-5) -- (3,-6) node[black,sloped,midway,above]{ Wind};
            \draw[-stealth,line width=2pt](-3,6) -- (-6,5) node[black,sloped,midway,above]{ Wind};
            \draw pic at (0,0) {waa-top={waacolor}{230.194428908}{0.15}};
            \draw[line width=2pt] (116.565051177:2) arc (116.565051177:140.194428908:2) node[midway,rotate=-53.7461622626,left] { Angle of Leeway};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <p>
          In order to compensate for the wind, the navigator must steer the waʻa into the wind by the same angle as the leeway angle. For example, if the waʻa needs to sail in the house Manu Malanai (SE) and the wind is pushing the waʻa one house further south, the waʻa will move in the house Nālani Malanai (SEbS). To maintain the course in the house Manu Malanai, the navigator must then point the waʻa one house north with an apparent heading in the house of Noio Malanai (SEbE) in order for the actual heading to be in the house of Manu Malanai (SE).
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
